rench <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":3,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Banastre was born in 1379, in Wheathill, Somerset, England, her father, William Banastre II, was 20 and her mother, Elizabeth Wellesley, was 16. She married Sir John De Stourton MP before 1403. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died from 1405 to 1416, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Charlton Musgrove, Somerset, England."},"et":{"1379–from 1405 to 1416":"1379–1405 kuni 1416","1379–1416":"1379–1416","1382–1495":"1382–1495","1384–1438":"1384–1438","1401–1472":"1401–1472","1359–1395":"1359–1395","1363–1383":"1363–1383","before 1403":"enne 1403","1363":"1363","1495":"1495","1395":"1395","1472":"1472","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1359":"1359","1379":"1379","1401":"1401","from 1405 to 1416":"1405 kuni 1416","1416":"1416","1438":"1438","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Preston, Dorset, England":"Preston, Dorset, England","Charlton Musgrove, Somerset, England":"Charlton Musgrove, Somerset, England","Radstock, Somerset, England":"Radstock, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Frome, Somerset, England":"Frome, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wheathill, Somerset, England":"Wheathill, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1379–from 1405 to 1416":"1379–vuodesta 1405 vuoteen 1416","1379–1416":"1379–1416","1382–1495":"1382–1495","1384–1438":"1384–1438","1401–1472":"1401–1472","1359–1395":"1359–1395","1363–1383":"1363–1383","before 1403":"ennen vuotta 1403","1363":"1363","1495":"1495","1395":"1395","1472":"1472","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1359":"1359","1379":"1379","1401":"1401","from 1405 to 1416":"vuodesta 1405 vuoteen 1416","1416":"1416","1438":"1438","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Preston, Dorset, England":"Preston, Dorset, England","Charlton Musgrove, Somerset, England":"Charlton Musgrove, Somerset, England","Radstock, Somerset, England":"Radstock, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Frome, Somerset, England":"Frome, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskun